escent]]\n[[Category:American people of Irish descent]]\n[[Category:American people of Polish-Jewish descent]]\n[[Category:American male stage actors]]\n[[Category:American male voice actors]]\n[[Category:Jewish American male actors]]\n[[Category:Living people]]\n[[Category:Male actors from New York City]]\n[[Category:Obie Award recipients]]\n[[Category:Tony Award winners]]\n[[Category:People from Greenwich Village]]\n[[Category:Walden School (New York City) alumni]]\n", "name_user": "Moe1810", "label": "safe", "comment": "\u2192\u200eTelevision", "url_page": "//en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Matthew_Broderick"}
{"title_page": "Liz Sheridan", "text_new": "{{Infobox person\n| name          = Liz Sheridan\n| image         =\n| imagesize     =\n| birth_name       = Elizabeth Ann Sheridan\n| birth_date    = {{birth date and age|1929|4|10}}\n| birth_place   = [[Rye, New York]], U.S.\n| occupation    = Actress\n| spouse        = {{Marriage|Dale Wales<br/>|1985|2003|reason=died}}\n| yearsactive   = \n| children       = 1\n}}\n\n'''Elizabeth Ann Sheridan''' (born April 10, 1929) is an American actress. She was born and raised in [[Rye, New York]], the daughter of concert singer Elizabeth Poole-Jones and classical pianist, Frank Sheridan.<ref>{{Cite web|url=https://www.nytimes.com/1926/11/18/archives/frank-sheridan-pianist-plays.html|title=Frank Sheridan, Pianist, Plays.|last=|first=|date=November 18, 1926|website=The New York Times|url-status=dead|archive-url=|archive-date=|access-date=April 8, 2020}}</ref><ref>{{Cite web|url=https://fr.wikipedia.org/wiki/Frank_Sheridan_(pianiste)|title=Frank Sheridan (pianiste)|last=|first=|date=|website=fr.wikipedia.org|url-status=live|archive-url=|archive-date=|access-date=}}</ref> While best known for her role as Jerry's mother in ''[[Seinfeld]]'', her decades-long career is extensive and includes work as a dancer, singer, and actress of stage and screen.<ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.filmreference.com/film/60/Liz-Sheridan.html|title=Liz Sheridan Biography (1929-)|author=|date=|work=filmreference.com|accessdate=16 March 2016}} While best known for her role in Seinfeld, her decades-long career is extensive and includes work as a dancer, singer, and actress of stage and screen.</ref>\n\n==Career==\nSheridan began her professional life in New York City and the Caribbean as a nightclub dancer and singer, moving on to stage work. She was cast in Broadway productions throughout the 1970s, both in musicals and plays.<ref>{{Cite web|url=https://www.ibdb.com/broadway-cast-staff/liz-sheridan-80515|title=Liz Sheridan|last=|first=|date=|website=Internet Broadway Database|url-status=live|archive-url=|archive-date=|access-date=}}</ref> Sheridan co-starred with [[Meryl Streep]] and [[Christopher Lloyd]] in the 1977's musical, ''[[Happy End (musical)|Happy End]]'', before moving to Los Angeles.<ref>{{Cite web|url=https://www.ibdb.com/broadway-production/happy-end-4000#OpeningNightCast|title=Happy End|last=|first=|date=|website=Internet Broadway Database|url-status=live|archive-url=|archive-date=|access-date=}}</ref> Working in Hollywood, she came to prominence in supporting roles in over a dozen feature films and 60 [[prime time]] network television movies, mini-series, and series including ''[[Kojak]]'', ''[[Archie Bunker's Place]]'', ''[[St. Elsewhere]]'', ''[[Newhart]]'', ''[[Moonlighting (TV series)|Moonlighting]]'', ''[[The A-Team]]'', ''[[Who's the Boss?|Who's the Boss]]'', ''[[Hill Street Blues|Hill St. Blues,]]'' ''[[Cagney & Lacey]]'', ''[[Family Ties]]'', and ''[[Murder, She Wrote]]''. Her first major role was playing nosy neighbor Raquel Ochmonek on the NBC TV series ''[[ALF (TV series)|ALF]]'', from 1986 to 1990. Following that she secured her most renowned and long-lived role, as [[Jerry Seinfeld (character)|Jerry Seinfeld]]'s mother, Helen, in the long-running and highly rated series, ''Seinfeld''.<ref>{{Cite web|url=https://www.businessinsider.com/the-20-best-tv-sitcoms-of-all-time-2013-6#1-seinfeld-20|title=The 20 Best TV Sitcoms Of All Time|last=Driscoll|first=Molly|date=June 8, 2013|website=Business Insider|url-status=live|archive-url=|archive-date=|access-date=}}</ref> She appeared in all nine seasons, from 1990 to 1998.<ref>{{cite web|url=https://www.imdb.com/name/nm0792210/filmoseries#tt0098904|title=Filmography by TV series for Liz Sheridan (I)|publisher=[[Internet Movie Database]]|accessdate=April 29, 2013}}</ref>  \n\nIn the 1950s and 1960s, she lived and worked in the Caribbean, \"singing and playing the piano in almost every bar and saloon in the West Indies.\"<ref name=\":0\" /> In the late 1960s, back in New York, she performed in one of Julius Monk's annual cabaret reviews at Plaza 9, located in the [[Plaza Hotel]].<ref>{{Cite web|url=https://www.quora.com/Was-there-a-club-in-New-York-City-in-the-1970s-called-Plaza-9-all-that-Jazz|title=Was there a club in New York City in the 1970s called \"Plaza 9 & all that Jazz?\"|last=Rose|first=David S.|date=2018|website=Quora|url-status=live|archive-url=|archive-date=|access-date=}}</ref> \n\nIn 2009, with [[Andy Griffith]] and [[Doris Roberts]], Sheridan co-starred in the feature film, ''[[Play the Game (2009 film)|Play the Game]]'', a romantic comedy about a lonely, [[Widow|widowed]] [[grandfather]] who, after a 60-year hiatus, learns dating tricks from his serial romancer of a grandson. The film stirred up [[controversy]] due to its [[Ageing|octogenarian]] [[Sex in film|sex scene]] between Sheridan and Griffith.<ref>{{Cite web|url=https://www.rogerebert.com/reviews/play-the-game-2009|title=Andy Griffith and Seinfeld's mom: I would really rather not know|last=Ebert|first=Roger|date=August 26, 2009|website=Roger Ebert|url-status=live|archive-url=|archive-date=|access-date=}}</ref><ref>{{cite news|last=Saslow|first=Rachel|url=https://www.washingtonpost.com/wp-dyn/content/article/2009/08/17/AR2009081702067.html|title=Media Scan: A Movie About Aging, a DVD for Exercise, a Book About Dieting|date=18 August 2009|work=Washington Post|accessdate=|url-status=live}}</ref>\n\n==Personal life==\nWhile working as a dancer in New York City nightclubs, Sheridan met the then-unknown [[James Dean]]. She wrote a book, ''Dizzy & Jimmy: My Life with James Dean: A Love Story'', chronicling their time together in 1952. In it, she describes them as each other's first romantic love. \"We had great times... We didn't want to be apart. We found a place and lived together... [b]efore he really hit it big.\"<ref>{{Cite web|url=https://www.youtube.com/watch?v=HlRm6HpQNJk&t=120s|title=Liz Sheridan Interview|last=|first=|date=November 11, 2009|website=YouTube|url-status=live|archive-url=|archive-date=|access-date=}}</ref> Dean pursued work on the stage in New York, with film roles in Hollywood soon to follow. Without sure footing or a serious plan, forging a future was not an option, thus bringing about the end of their relationship.<ref>{{Cite book|last=Spoto|first=Donald|title=Rebel: The Life and Legend of James Dean|publisher=Harper Collins|year=1996|isbn=978-0060176563|location=New York, New York|pages=95\u2013122}}</ref><ref>{{Cite web|url=https://www.youtube.com/watch?v=bcf165OjUms|title=Liz Sheridan Interview on The Paul Leslie Hour|last=Leslie|first=Paul|date=March 2, 2012|website=YouTube|url-status=live|archive-url=|archive-date=|access-date=}}</ref> \"He was being hauled away into this career, and I couldn't follow him,\" she said in an interview.<ref>{{Cite web|url=https://people.com/archive/an-affair-to-remember-vol-45-no-25/|title=An Affair to Remember|last=Lipton|first=Michael A.|date=June 24, 1996|website=People magazine|url-status=dead|archive-url=https://people.com/archive/an-affair-to-remember-vol-45-no-25/|archive-date=June 24, 1996|access-date=April 6, 2020}}</ref><ref>{{Cite book|last=Winkler|first=Peter|title=The Real James Dean: Intimate Memories from Those Who Knew Him Best|publisher=Chicago Review Press|year=2016|isbn=978-1613734728|location=Chicago, IL|pages=138}}</ref> \n\nEarly in 1953, Sheridan departed New York for the Virgin Islands.<ref name=\":0\">{{Cite book|last=Sheridan|first=Liz|title=Dizzy & Jimmy: My Life with James Dean: a Love Story|publisher=Harper Entertainment|year=2000|isbn=978-0060393830|location=New York, NY|pages=298}}</ref> She lived for over a decade in St. Thomas and later Puerto Rico. She earned a living as a dancer and also by singing and playing piano. Together with a neighbor who had a dance troupe, she won a dance contest she choreographed for the first Carnival in St. Thomas. She also earned a six hundred dollar purse finishing first in a horse race, atop her mare, General\u00e9. After a brief engagement to a man, Justus Villa (aka Pancho), she realized she didn't want to marry him, broke it off, and returned, for a time, to New York City. There, at a party, she again met up with Dean. Afterwards, in a cab, he told her, \"Nothing's lost between us. It never will be. You're a part of me and I'm a part of you. I take you with me wherever I go.\" That was the last time she saw him.<ref>{{Cite book|last=Sheridan|first=Liz|title=Dizzy & Jimmy: My Life with James Dean: a Love Story|publisher=Harper Entertainment|year=2000|isbn=978-0060393830|location=New York, NY|pages=306\u2013319}}</ref>  Back in the Caribbean, in Puerto Rico, she met jazz musician [William] Dale Wales (1917\u20132003)<ref>{{Cite web|url=https://www.myheritage.com/research/record-10182-2227934/william-dale-wales-in-biographical-summaries-of-notable-people|title=Dale Wales|last=|first=|date=|website=My Heritage|url-status=live|archive-url=|archive-date=|access-date=}}</ref><ref>{{Cite book|last=Kelley|first=Robin|title=Thelonious Monk: The Life and Times of an American Original|publisher=Free Press|year=2009|isbn=978-0684831909|location=New York, NY|pages=227, 229}}</ref> in Puerto Rico. They shared a life from 1960 until his death; they wed in 1985.<ref>{{cite web|last=|first= |url=https://www.imdb.com/name/nm0792210/bio?ref_=nm_ov_bio_sm|title=Biography: Spouse|publisher=imdb.com|date= |accessdate=2016-06-12}}</ref> Their daughter is a photographer living in New York City's [[Greenwich Village]].\n\nLiz Sheridan and actress [[Elizabeth Montgomery]] were best friends: Dizzy and Lizzie. Montgomery only took on the nickname \"Lizzie\" following her performance in the Emmy Award winning TV movie, ''[[The Legend of Lizzie Borden]]''; Dizzy was a shortened version of \"Dizabeth,\" which is how her sister managed to pronounce her name when they were young.<ref>{{Cite book|last=Pilato|first=Herbie J.|title=Twitch Upon a Star: The Bewitched Life and Career of Elizabeth Montgomery|publisher=Taylor Trade|year=2012|isbn=978-1589797499|location=Lanham, MD|pages=6, 358, 366}}</ref><ref>{{Cite web|url=https://www.imdb.com/name/nm0792210/bio|title=Liz Sheridan Biography|last=|first=|date=|website=IMDb|url-status=live|archive-url=|archive-date=|access-date=}}</ref><ref>{{Cite web|url=https://www.youtube.com/watch?v=bcf165OjUms|title=Liz Sheridan Interview on The Paul Leslie Hour|last=Leslie|first=Paul|date=March 2, 2012|website=YouTube|url-status=live|archive-url=|archive-date=|access-date=}}</ref>\n\n==References==\n{{Reflist}}\n\n==External links==\n* {{IMDb name|0792210}}\n\n{{Authority control}}\n\n{{DEFAULTSORT:Sheridan, Liz}}\n[[Category:1929 births]]\n[[Category:Living people]]\n[[Category:20th-century American actresses]]\n[[Category:21st-century American actresses]]\n[[Category:Actresses from New York (state)]]\n[[Category:American female dancers]]\n[[Category:American dancers]]\n[[Category:American film actresses]]\n[[Category:American stage actresses]]\n[[Category:American television actresses]]\n[[Category:American musical theatre actresses]]\n[[Category:American voice actresses]]\n[[Category:People from Westchester County, New York]]\n[[Category:Dancers from New York (state)]]\n", "text_old": "{{Infobox person\n| name          = Liz Sheridan\n| image         =\n| imagesize     =\n| birth_name       = Elizabeth Ann Sheridan\n| birth_date    = {{birth date and age|1929|4|10}}\n| birth_place   = [[Rye, New York]], U.S.\n| occupation    = Actress\n| spouse        = {{Marriage|Dale Wales<br/>|1985|2003|reason=died}}\n| yearsactive   = \n| children       = 1\n}}\n\n'''Elizabeth Ann Sheridan''' (born April 10, 1929) is an American actress. She was born and raised in [[Rye, New York]], the daughter of concert singer Elizabeth Poole-Jones and classical pianist, Frank Sheridan.<ref>{{Cite web|url=https://www.nytimes.com/1926/11/18/archives/frank-sheridan-pianist-plays.html|title=Frank Sheridan, Pianist, Plays.|last=|first=|date=November 18, 1926|website=The New York Times|url-status=dead|archive-url=|archive-date=|access-date=April 8, 2020}}</ref><ref>{{Cite web|url=https://fr.wikipedia.org/wiki/Frank_Sheridan_(pianiste)|title=Frank Sheridan (pianiste)|last=|first=|date=|website=fr.wikipedia.org|url-status=live|archive-url=|archive-date=|access-date=}}</ref> While best known for her role as Jerry's mother in ''[[Seinfeld]]'', her decades-long career is extensive and includes work as a dancer, singer, and actress of stage and screen.<ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.filmreference.com/film/60/Liz-Sheridan.html|title=Liz Sheridan Biography (1929-)|author=|date=|work=filmreference.com|accessdate=16 March 2016}} While best known for her role in Seinfeld, her decades-long career is extensive and includes work as a dancer, singer, and actress of stage and screen.</ref>\n\n==Career==\nSheridan began her professional life in New York City and the Caribbean as a nightclub dancer and singer, moving on to stage work. She was cast in Broadway productions throughout the 1970s, both in musicals and plays.<ref>{{Cite web|url=https://www.ibdb.com/broadway-cast-staff/liz-sheridan-80515|title=Liz Sheridan|last=|first=|date=|website=Internet Broadway Database|url-status=live|archive-url=|archive-date=|access-date=}}</ref> Sheridan co-starred with [[Meryl Streep]] and [[Christopher Lloyd]] in the 1977's musical, ''[[Happy End (musical)|Happy End]]'', before moving to Los Angeles.<ref>{{Cite web|url=https://www.ibdb.com/broadway-production/happy-end-4000#OpeningNightCast|title=Happy End|last=|first=|date=|website=Internet Broadway Database|url-status=live|archive-url=|archive-date=|access-date=}}</ref> Working in Hollywood, she came to prominence in supporting roles in over a dozen feature films and 60 [[prime time]] network television movies, mini-series, and series including ''[[Kojak]]'', ''[[Archie Bunker's Place]]'', ''[[St. Elsewhere]]'', ''[[Newhart]]'', ''[[Moonlighting (TV series)|Moonlighting]]'', ''[[The A-Team]]'', ''[[Who's the Boss?|Who's the Boss]]'', ''[[Hill Street Blues|Hill St. Blues,]]'' ''[[Cagney & Lacey]]'', ''[[Family Ties]]'', and ''[[Murder, She Wrote]]''. Her first major role was playing nosy neighbor Raquel Ochmonek on the NBC TV series ''[[ALF (TV series)|ALF]]'', from 1986 to 1990. Following that she secured her most renowned and long-lived role, as [[Jerry Seinfeld (character)|Jerry Seinfeld]]'s mother, Helen, in the long-running and highly rated series, ''Seinfeld''.<ref>{{Cite web|url=https://www.businessinsider.com/the-20-best-tv-sitcoms-of-all-time-2013-6#1-seinfeld-20|title=The 20 Best TV Sitcoms Of All Time|last=Driscoll|first=Molly|date=June 8, 2013|website=Business Insider|url-status=live|archive-url=|archive-date=|access-date=}}</ref> She appeared in all nine seasons, from 1990 to 1998.<ref>{{cite web|url=https://www.imdb.com/name/nm0792210/filmoseries#tt0098904|title=Filmography by TV series for Liz Sheridan (I)|publisher=[[Internet Movie Database]]|accessdate=April 29, 2013}}</ref>  \n\nIn the 1950s and 1960s, she lived and worked in the Caribbean, \"singing and playing the piano in almost every bar and saloon in the West Indies.\"<ref name=\":0\" /> In the late 1960s, back in New York, she performed in one of Julius Monk's annual cabaret reviews at Plaza 9, located in the [[Plaza Hotel]].<ref>{{Cite web|url=https://www.quora.com/Was-there-a-club-in-New-York-City-in-the-1970s-called-Plaza-9-all-that-Jazz|title=Was there a club in New York City in the 1970s called \"Plaza 9 & all that Jazz?\"|last=Rose|first=David S.|date=2018|website=Quora|url-status=live|archive-url=|archive-date=|access-date=}}</ref> \n\nIn 2009, with [[Andy Griffith]] and [[Doris Roberts]], Sheridan co-starred in the feature film, ''[[Play the Game (2009 film)|Play the Game]]'', a romantic comedy about a lonely, [[Widow|widowed]] [[grandfather]] who, after a 60-year hiatus, learns dating tricks from his serial romancer of a grandson. The film stirred up [[controversy]] due to its [[Ageing|octogenarian]] [[Sex in film|sex scene]] between Sheridan and Griffith.<ref>{{Cite web|url=https://www.rogerebert.com/reviews/play-the-game-2009|title=Andy Griffith and Seinfeld's mom: I would really rather not know|last=Ebert|first=Roger|date=August 26, 2009|website=Roger Ebert|url-status=live|archive-url=|archive-date=|access-date=}}</ref><ref>{{cite news|last=Saslow|first=Rachel|url=https://www.washingtonpost.com/wp-dyn/content/article/2009/08/17/AR2009081702067.html|title=Media Scan: A Movie About Aging, a DVD for Exercise, a Book About Dieting|date=18 August 2009|work=Washington Post|accessdate=|url-status=live}}</ref>\n\n==Personal life==\nWhile working as a dancer in New York City nightclubs, Sheridan met the then-unknown [[James Dean]]. She wrote a book, ''Dizzy & Jimmy: My Life with James Dean: A Love Story'', chronicling their time together in 1952. In it, she describes them as each other's first romantic love. \"We had great times... We didn't want to be apart. We found a place and lived together... [b]efore he really hit it big.\"<ref>{{Cite web|url=https://www.youtube.com/watch?v=HlRm6HpQNJk&t=120s|title=Liz Sheridan Interview|last=|first=|date=November 11, 2009|website=YouTube|url-status=live|archive-url=|archive-date=|access-date=}}</ref> Dean pursued work on the stage in New York, with film roles in Hollywood soon to follow. Without sure footing or a serious plan, forging a future was not an option, thus bringing about the end of their relationship.<ref>{{Cite book|last=Spoto|first=Donald|title=Rebel: The Life and Legend of James Dean|publisher=Harper Collins|year=1996|isbn=978-0060176563|location=New York, New York|pages=95\u2013122}}</ref><ref>{{Cite web|url=https://www.youtube.com/watch?v=bcf165OjUms|title=Liz Sheridan Interview on The Paul Leslie Hour|last=Leslie|first=Paul|date=March 2, 2012|website=YouTube|url-status=live|archive-url=|archive-date=|access-date=}}</ref> \"He was being hauled away into this career, and I couldn't follow him,\" she said in an interview.<ref>{{Cite web|url=https://people.com/archive/an-affair-to-remember-vol-45-no-25/|title=An Affair to Remember|last=Lipton|first=Michael A.|date=June 24, 1996|website=People magazine|url-status=dead|archive-url=https://people.com/archive/an-affair-to-remember-vol-45-no-25/|archive-date=June 24, 1996|access-date=April 6, 2020}}</ref><ref>{{Cite book|last=Winkler|first=Peter|title=The Real James Dean: Intimate Memories from Those Who Knew Him Best|publisher=Chicago Review Press|year=2016|isbn=978-1613734728|location=Chicago, IL|pages=138}}</ref> \n\nEarly in 1953, Sheridan departed New York for the Virgin Islands.<ref name=\":0\">{{Cite book|last=Sheridan|first=Liz|title=Dizzy & Jimmy: My Life with James Dean: a Love Story|publisher=Harper Entertainment|year=2000|isbn=978-0060393830|location=New York, NY|pages=298}}</ref> She lived for over a decade in St. Thomas and later Puerto Rico. She earned a living as a dancer and also by singing and playing piano. Together with a neighbor who had a dance troupe, she won a dance contest she choreographed for the first Carnival in St. Thomas. She also earned a six hundred dollar purse finishing first in a horse race, atop her mare, General\u00e9. After a brief engagement to a man, Justus Villa (aka Pancho), she realized realized she didn't want to marry him, broke it off, and returned, for a time, to New York City. There, at a party, she again met up with Dean. Afterwards, in a cab, he told her, \"Nothing's lost between us. It never will be. You're a part of me and I'm a part of you. I take you with me wherever I go.\" That was the last time she saw him.<ref>{{Cite book|last=Sheridan|first=Liz|title=Dizzy & Jimmy: My Life with James Dean: a Love Story|publisher=Harper Entertainment|year=2000|isbn=978-0060393830|location=New York, NY|pages=306\u2013319}}</ref>  Back in the Caribbean, in Puerto Rico, she met jazz musician [William] Dale Wales (1917\u20132003)<ref>{{Cite web|url=https://www.myheritage.com/research/record-10182-2227934/william-dale-wales-in-biographical-summaries-of-notable-people|title=Dale Wales|last=|first=|date=|website=My Heritage|url-status=live|archive-url=|archive-date=|access-date=}}</ref><ref>{{Cite book|last=Kelley|first=Robin|title=Thelonious Monk: The Life and Times of an American Original|publisher=Free Press|year=2009|isbn=978-0684831909|location=New York, NY|pages=227, 229}}</ref> in Puerto Rico. They shared a life from 1960 until his death; they wed in 1985.<ref>{{cite web|last=|first= |url=https://www.imdb.com/name/nm0792210/bio?ref_=nm_ov_bio_sm|title=Biography: Spouse|publisher=imdb.com|date= |accessdate=2016-06-12}}</ref> Their daughter is a photographer living in New York City's [[Greenwich Village]].\n\nLiz Sheridan and actress [[Elizabeth Montgomery]] were best friends: Dizzy and Lizzie. Montgomery only took on the nickname \"Lizzie\" following her performance in the Emmy Award winning TV movie, ''[[The Legend of Lizzie Borden]]''; Dizzy was a shortened version of \"Dizabeth,\" which is how her sister managed to pronounce her name when they were young.<ref>{{Cite book|last=Pilato|first=Herbie J.|title=Twitch Upon a Star: The Bewitched Life and Career of Elizabeth Montgomery|publisher=Taylor Trade|year=2012|isbn=978-1589797499|location=Lanham, MD|pages=6, 358, 366}}</ref><ref>{{Cite web|url=https://www.imdb.com/name/nm0792210/bio|title=Liz Sheridan Biography|last=|first=|date=|website=IMDb|url-status=live|archive-url=|archive-date=|access-date=}}</ref><ref>{{Cite web|url=https://www.youtube.com/watch?v=bcf165OjUms|title=Liz Sheridan Interview on The Paul Leslie Hour|last=Leslie|first=Paul|date=March 2, 2012|website=YouTube|url-status=live|archive-url=|archive-date=|access-date=}}</ref>\n\n==References==\n{{Reflist}}\n\n==External links==\n* {{IMDb name|0792210}}\n\n{{Authority control}}\n\n{{DEFAULTSORT:Sheridan, Liz}}\n[[Category:1929 births]]\n[[Category:Living people]]\n[[Category:20th-century American actresses]]\n[[Category:21st-century American actresses]]\n[[Category:Actresses from New York (state)]]\n[[Category:American female dancers]]\n[[Category:American dancers]]\n[[Category:American film actresses]]\n[[Category:American stage actresses]]\n[[Category:American television actresses]]\n[[Category:American musical theatre actresses]]\n[[Category:American voice actresses]]\n[[Category:People from Westchester County, New York]]\n[[Category:Dancers from New York (state)]]\n", "name_user": "Teleutomyrmex", "label": "safe", "comment": "double", "url_page": "//en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Liz_Sheridan"}
{"title_page": "2015 World Junior Ice Hockey Championships", "text_new": "{{redirect|2015 World Juniors|other championships|World Junior Championships (disambiguation){{!}}World Junior Championships}}\n{{Use mdy dates|date=June 2013}}\n{{Infobox International Ice Hockey Competition\n| tourney_name = IIHF World U20 Championship\n| year = 2015\n| other_titles =\n| image = 2015 WJHC logo.svg\n| size = 160\n| caption =\n| country = Canada\n| dates = December 26, 2014 \u2013 January 5, 2015\n| num_teams = 10\n| venues = [[Air Canada Centre]], [[Toronto]]<br />[[Bell Centre]], [[Montreal]]\n| cities = 2\n| winners_other = {{ihj|CAN}}\n| count = 16\n| second_other = {{ihj|RUS}}\n| third_other = {{ihj|SVK}}\n| fourth_other = {{ihj|SWE}}\n| games = 30\n| goals = 176\n| attendance = 366370\n| website = [http://www.worldjunior2015.com 2015 World Juniors]\n| scoring_leader = {{flagicon|CAN}} [[Sam Reinhart]]\n| points = 11 \n| mvp = {{flagicon|SVK}} [[Denis Godla]]\n| prevseason = [[2014 World Junior Ice Hockey Championships|2014]]\n| nextseason = [[2016 World Junior Ice Hockey Championships|2016]]\n}}\nThe '''2015 World Junior Ice Hockey Championships''' was the 39th edition of [[IIHF World U20 Championship|Ice Hockey World Junior Championship]], played from December 26, 2014 to January 5, 2015. It was co-hosted by [[Toronto]], [[Ontario]], and [[Montreal]], [[Quebec]], [[Canada]],<ref name=\"Future\">{{cite web|title=Canada to host more tourneys |url=http://www.iihf.com/channels/iihf-world-championship-oc09/home/news/news-singleview-world-championship-2009/article/canada-to-host-more-tourneys.html |date=May 9, 2010 |accessdate=January 5, 2011 |publisher=International Ice Hockey Federation |url-status=dead |archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20121018123039/http://www.iihf.com/channels/iihf-world-championship-oc09/home/news/news-singleview-world-championship-2009/article/canada-to-host-more-tourneys.html |archivedate=October 18, 2012 }}</ref> and organized by [[Hockey Canada]], [[Hockey Quebec]], the [[Ontario Hockey Federation]], the [[Montreal Canadiens]], [[Maple Leafs Sports and Entertainment]] and [[Evenko]].<ref>[http://www.iihf.com/home-of-hockey/news/news-singleview/recap/8011.html?tx_ttnews%5BbackPid%5D=10&cHash=5d06d23b71 \"Heading to hockey\u2019s meccas\"] {{Webarchive|url=https://web.archive.org/web/20130629032627/http://www.iihf.com/home-of-hockey/news/news-singleview/recap/8011.html?tx_ttnews%5BbackPid%5D=10&cHash=5d06d23b71 |date=June 29, 2013 }}, IIHF.com. June 20, 2013</ref> Games were split between [[Air Canada Centre]] in Toronto and [[Bell Centre]] in Montreal, with Montreal hosting Group A matches and two quarter finals, and Toronto hosting Group B, along with the relegation games, two quarter finals, along with the semi-finals, bronze medal, and gold medal games.<ref name=CTV-2013-06-20>[http://www.ctvnews.ca/sports/montreal-and-toronto-to-host-2015-2017-world-junior-championships-1.1333912 \"Montreal and Toronto to host 2015, 2017 world junior championships\"], Canadian Press, June 20, 2013</ref><ref name=Gazette-2013-06-20>The Gazette (Montreal), [https://montrealgazette.com/sports/World+Junior+Championship+coming+town/8555635/story.html \"World Junior Championship is coming to town\"] {{Webarchive|url=https://web.archive.org/web/20130625043836/http://www.montrealgazette.com/sports/World+Junior+Championship+coming+town/8555635/story.html |date=June 25, 2013 }}, Brenda Branswell, June 20, 2013</ref>\n\nAfter failing to medal at the previous two editions of the tournament, [[Canada men's national junior ice hockey team|Canada]] beat [[Russia men's national junior ice hockey team|Russia]] in the final to win the gold medal, marking Canada's first medal at the World Juniors since 2012, and Canada's first gold since [[2009 World Junior Ice Hockey Championships|2009]]. [[Slovakia men's national junior ice hockey team|Slovakia]] defeated [[Sweden men's national junior ice hockey team|Sweden]] in the bronze medal game to win their second-ever medal. [[Germany men's national junior ice hockey team|Germany]] finished tenth overall and was relegated to Division IA for the 2016 tournament. Slovak goaltender [[Denis Godla]] was named the tournament's most valuable player, while [[Sam Reinhart]] of Canada was the scoring leader with 11 points.\n\n== Player eligibility ==\nA player is eligible to play in the 2015 World Junior Ice Hockey Championships if:<ref name=\"Main requirements for eligibility\">{{cite web |url=http://www.iihf.com/fileadmin/user_upload/PDF/The_IIHF/2012-2014_IIHF_Statutes_and_Bylaws.pdf |title=IIHF statutes and bylaws |publisher=[[International Ice Hockey Federation|IIHF]] |accessdate=2014-01-01}}</ref>\n* the player is of male gender;\n* the player was born at the earliest in 1995, and at the latest, in 2000;\n* the player is a citizen in the country he represents;\n* the player is under the jurisdiction of a national association that is a member of the [[International Ice Hockey Federation|IIHF]].\n\nIf a player who has never played in IIHF-organized competition wishes to switch national eligibility, he must have played in competitions for two consecutive years in the new country without playing in another country, as well as show his move to the new country's national association with an international transfer card. In case the player has previously played in IIHF-organized competition but wishes to switch national eligibility, he must have played in competitions for four consecutive years in the new country without playing in another country, he must show his move to the new country's national association with an international transfer card, as well as be a citizen of the new country. A player may only switch national eligibility once.<ref name=\"Requirements for switching national eligibility\">{{cite web |url=http://www.iihf.com/home-of-hockey/championships/iihf-eligibility.html |title=IIHF Eligibility |publisher=[[International Ice Hockey Federation|IIHF]] |accessdate=2014-01-01}}</ref>\n\n==Top Division==\n===Venues===\n{| class=\"wikitable\" style=\"text-align:center;\"\n! [[Toronto]]\n!rowspan=5 colspan=2|{{Location map+ |Canada |width=350 |float=center |caption= |places=\n{{Location map~ |Canada |lat=45.508889 |long=-73.561667 |label=[[Montreal]]|position=right}}\n{{Location map~ |Canada |lat=43.741667 |long=-79.373333 |label=[[Toronto]]|position=left}}\n}}\n! [[Montreal]]\n|-\n! [[Air Canada Centre]]<br/>Capacity: 18,819\n! [[Bell Centre]]<br />Capacity: 21,287\n|-\n| [[File:Air Canada Centre and CN Tower from Bay St.jpg|150px]]\n| [[File:CentreBell.jpg|150px]]\n|}\n\n===Officials===\nThe [[IIHF]] selected 12 referees and 10 linesmen to officiate during the tournament:<ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.worldjunior2015.com/en/news/officials-known/|title=Officials Known|publisher=IIHF.com|accessdate=5 December 2014}}</ref>\n\n{{col-begin}}\n{{col-3}}\n'''Referees'''\n* {{flagicon|SVK}} Vladim\u00edr Balu\u0161ka\n* {{flagicon|GER}} Lars Bruggemann\n* {{flagicon|RUS}} Roman Gofman\n* {{flagicon|CZE}} Antonin Je\u0159\u00e1bek\n* {{flagicon|FIN}} Mikko Kaukokari\n* {{flagicon|USA}} Geoffrey Miller\n* {{flagicon|SWE}} Linus \u00d6hlund\n* {{flagicon|RUS}} Konstantin Olenin\n* {{flagicon|USA}} Steve Patafie\n* {{flagicon|CAN}} Pascal St-Jaques\n* {{flagicon|SWE}} Marcus Vinnerborg\n* {{flagicon|SUI}} Tobias Wehrli\n{{col-3}}\n'''Linesmen'''\n* {{flagicon|CAN}} Jordan Browne\n* {{flagicon|FRA}} Pierre Dehaen\n* {{flagicon|RUS}} Gleb Lazarev\n* {{flagicon|CZE}} Miroslav Lhotsk\u00fd\n* {{flagicon|SWE}} Andreas Malmqvist\n* {{flagicon|CAN}} Bevan Mills\n* {{flagicon|FIN}} Jani Pesonen\n* {{flagicon|GER}} Nikolaj Ponomarjow\n* {{flagicon|USA}} Judson Ritter\n* {{flagicon|SUI}} Simon Wust\n{{col-3}}\n{{col-end}}\n\n===Format===\nThe four best ranked teams from each group of the preliminary round advance to the quarterfinals, while the last placed teams from each group played a relegation round in a [[Playoff format#Best-of-three playoff|best of three]] format to determine the relegated team.<ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.iihf.com/home-of-hockey/news/news-singleview/?tx_ttnews%5Btt_news%5D=7006&cHash=3fc42c5c221ed1fe6cdb1b0461a9ce05|title=New format for U18, U20 Worlds|date=2012-05-29|work=[[IIHF]].com|accessdate=2011-05-29}}</ref>\n\n===Rosters===\n{{Main|2015 World Junior Ice Hockey Championships rosters}}\n\n=== Preliminary round ===\n<small>''All times are local. ([[Eastern Time Zone|Eastern Standard Time]] \u2013 [[UTC-5]])''</small>\n\n{| class=\"wikitable\"\n|-\n| style=\"background:#ccffcc;width:22px\" |\n|Team qualified to Quarterfinals\n|-\n| style=\"background:#ffcccc;\" |\n|Team will play in Relegation round\n|}\n\n====Group A====\n{{iht header}}\n{{iht team|t={{ihj|CAN}}|w=4|ow=0|ol=0|l=0|gf=21|ga=4|bc=#ccffcc}}\n{{iht team|t={{ihj|USA}}|w=2|ow=1|ol=0|l=1|gf=14|ga=6|bc=#ccffcc}}\n{{iht team|t={{ihj|SVK}}|w=2|ow=0|ol=0|l=2|gf=7|ga=14|bc=#ccffcc}}\n{{iht team|t={{ihj|FIN}}|w=1|ow=0|ol=1|l=2|gf=5|ga=8|bc=#ccffcc}}\n{{iht team|t={{ihj|GER}}|w=0|ow=0|ol=0|l=4|gf=2|ga=17|bc=#ffcccc}}\n|}\n\n{{IceHockeybox\n| date = December 26, 2014\n| time = 15:00\n| team1 = {{ihj-rt|FIN}}\n| score = 1\u20132 <small> [[Shootout (ice hockey)|GWS]] </small>\n| team2 = '''{{ihj|USA}}'''\n| progression = 1\u20130<br>1\u20131\n| periods = (1\u20131, 0\u20130, 0\u20130)<br>([[sudden death overtime|OT]] 0\u20130)<br>([[Shootout (ice hockey)|SO]]: 1\u20132)\n| goalie1 = [[Ville Husso]]\n| goalie2 = [[Thatcher Demko]]\n| goals1 = [[Mikko Rantanen|M. Rantanen]] \u2013 01:22\n| soshots1 = [[Artturi Lehkonen|A. Lehkonen]] {{SOgoal}}<br>[[Juuso Ikonen|J. Ikonen]] {{SOmiss}}<br>[[Kasperi Kapanen|K. Kapanen]] {{SOmiss}}\n| goals2 = <br>13:54 \u2013 [[Alex Tuch|A. Tuch]] ([[Jack Eichel|J. Eichel]], [[Tony DeAngelo|A. DeAngelo]]) (PP)\n| soshots2 = {{SOgoal}} J. Eichel<br>{{SOmiss}} [[Sonny Milano|S. Milano]]<br>{{SOgoal}} [[Chase de Leo|C. de Leo]]\n| attendance = 8,006\n| stadium = [[Bell Centre]]\n| official = {